k+(k+1) &= n \\
k(k+1) &= m
\end{align*}
Since $m$ is divisible by 3, either $k$ or $k+1$ must be divisible by 3. We can consider two cases:
Case 1: $k$ is divisible by 3. Then $k+1$ is not divisible by 3. Since $k$ is divisible by 3, we can write $k=3p$ for some integer $p$. Substituting this into the equations above, we get:
\begin{align*}
3p+(3p+1) &= n \\
3p(3p+1) &= m
\end{align*}
Simplifying, we get:
\begin{align*}
6p+1 &= n \\
9p^2+3p &= m
\end{align*}
Since $m$ is divisible by 3, $9p^2+3p$ must also be divisible by 3. This implies that $p$ must be divisible by 3. Let $p=3q$ for some integer $q$. Substituting this into the equations above, we get:
